#TeaganAir
Flight log books are now officially in use. I have 2.3 hours of flight records ^_^
#TeaganAir
If I were to describe what it feels like to fly a small plane, I would say it's like riding a motorcycle/atv/dinghy combination at 4000 feet above ground.
On the ground, things change rapidly. There is a certain amount of instability, so an atv/motorcycle is needed.
Additionally, you might not know that when driving the plane on the ground, you control direction with your feet, not a yoke. You use rudder pedals and brakes. It's not a car.
In the air, you'll experience bumps and shakes, feeling like you're sailing a boat on water. Even though you can control the plane, sometimes the airflow can make you a bit disoriented, so you need to adapt to flying in the air, just as sailors adapt to sailing.
There's also a random fun fact about this:
Flying is very strenuous. Today my back and legs are sore, feeling like I've been to the gym.
This isn't just a Sunday drive. As a beginner, it seems more like a sport than a cruise.
Dear friends, Happy Saturday. Welcome to 4000 feet above ground.
I will fly again tomorrow, we will practice stall and slow flight.
The weather wasn't very stable today, but it was super fun. We practiced slow flight and stalls. Our ground speed dropped to 16 miles per hour while our airspeed was still 65 miles per hour.
Today the weather was clear, though there was some haze up high, the view was still great.
